{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_99","type":"agent_message","text":"Completed the research run end-to-end. The main deliverables are [REPORT.md](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/REPORT.md), [README.md](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/README.md), [planning.md](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/planning.md), and the experiment script [src/run_layernorm_study.py](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/src/run_layernorm_study.py).\n\nThe result is mixed but clear. In this GPT-2-family comparison, LN removal strongly changed internal geometry: OCW clue anisotropy dropped from `0.9915` to `0.9642` and effective rank rose from `1.35` to `2.56`, both significant after FDR correction. But creative-output diversity did not improve in a straightforward way: `distinct_1` and `distinct_2` both fell slightly, while semantic spread across generations increased (`0.803` to `0.831`, FDR `p=0.024`). The defensible conclusion is that LayerNorm appears to compress representation geometry, but removing it alone did not reliably unlock better lexical creativity or stronger association performance in this setup.\n\nResults and raw artifacts are in [results/layernorm_study](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/results/layernorm_study), with figures in [figures/layernorm_study](/workspaces/layernorm-concept-assoc-65c1-codex/figures/layernorm_study). I also reran the full experiment with the same seed into `results/layernorm_study_rerun`; the primary CSV outputs were byte-identical, so the run is reproducible in this environment. The main caveat is hardware: GPUs were present, but Torch fell back to CPU because the installed CUDA build expected a newer driver."}}
